/-
Conjecture Cj.18 — Emergence has a renormalization-group (RG) structure with
universal fixed points.

Reference: `~/Desktop/MIP/conjectures/index.md`
  * Cj.18 entry, line 35 ("Cj.18 | 涌现重整化群和普适性 | R.66 | 开放：需要尺度
    变换不变性");
  * meta-theory grouping, line ~871 ("完备性 / 元理论：Cj.11, Cj.7, Cj.13,
    Cj.18").

================================================================================
FAITHFUL NL CONJECTURE
================================================================================
Emergence carries a renormalization-group structure: there is a scale-coarse-
graining map (an RG transformation `Rg`) acting on the space of "emergence
configurations / coupling constants", whose iteration is the RG flow, and this
flow has a UNIVERSAL fixed point `c*` (`Rg c* = c*`) toward which a basin of
configurations flows.  Universality means a whole class of microscopically
different configurations flow to the SAME fixed point, so their large-scale
critical behaviour coincides (the universality classes of Cj.7).

================================================================================
FORMALIZATION CHOICES
================================================================================
We abstract the RG data as:
  * a type `C` of configurations / coupling vectors;
  * an RG transformation `Rg : C → C` (one coarse-graining step);
  * the flow `Rg^[n]` (n-fold iteration), which is `Function.iterate`.

A FIXED POINT is `Function.IsFixedPt Rg c*`, i.e. `Rg c* = c*`.  We formalize the
two structural facts that any genuine RG theory must satisfy and that ARE
provable for an abstractly given `Rg`:

  (FP1) a fixed point is invariant under the entire flow: `Rg^[n] c* = c*`;
  (FP2) UNIVERSALITY (basin form): if every configuration in a basin `B` flows to
        `c*` (`Rg^[n] c → c*` along the flow, modelled here by EVENTUAL arrival
        `∃ n, Rg^[n] c = c*` for the exactly-attracted case), then all of `B`
        shares the same fixed point — the defining feature of a universality
        class.

These are theorems about ANY given `Rg`.  What CANNOT be supplied from A.1-A.4 is
the RG map `Rg` ITSELF (the scale-coarse-graining on emergence configurations)
and the assertion that ITS fixed point is universal — that requires
scale-transformation invariance, absent from the axioms.

================================================================================
VERDICT: OPEN.
================================================================================
The full conjecture — that EMERGENCE (as defined by A.1-A.4) possesses an RG map
with a universal fixed point — is OPEN and not derivable from A.1-A.4.  We give a
faithful `Prop` statement (`Cj18_Statement`) recording exactly "∃ RG flow with a
universal fixed point", and prove the structural fixed-point/universality
LEMMAS (FP1, FP2) that hold for any abstract `Rg`.  These lemmas show the
STATEMENT is well-formed and that, GIVEN such an `Rg`, its consequences are
exactly the RG-universality picture — but they do NOT (and cannot) construct
`Rg` from the axioms.  See "BLOCKED AT".

This file is `sorry`-free and `axiom`-free.
-/
import Mathlib.Dynamics.FixedPoints.Basic
import Mathlib.Logic.Function.Iterate

namespace MIP

namespace Cj18

variable {C : Type}

/-- The n-step RG flow generated by a one-step RG transformation `Rg`. -/
def rgFlow (Rg : C → C) (n : ℕ) : C → C := Rg^[n]

/-- A configuration `c⋆` is an RG fixed point iff `Rg c⋆ = c⋆`. -/
def IsRGFixedPoint (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C) : Prop := Function.IsFixedPt Rg cstar

/-- **(FP1) A fixed point is invariant under the entire RG flow.**

If `Rg c⋆ = c⋆`, then `Rg^[n] c⋆ = c⋆` for all `n`: the flow leaves the fixed
point in place at every scale.  This is the basic consistency of a fixed point
with the flow. -/
theorem rgFlow_fixed (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C)
    (h : IsRGFixedPoint Rg cstar) (n : ℕ) :
    rgFlow Rg n cstar = cstar :=
  Function.IsFixedPt.iterate h n

/-- **(FP2) Universality / basin coincidence.**

If two configurations `c₁`, `c₂` are each EXACTLY attracted to fixed points
`c⋆₁`, `c⋆₂` (some finite number of RG steps lands them on the fixed point), and
they reach the SAME fixed point, then their large-scale (flowed) behaviour
coincides at and beyond the arrival scales.  We state the clean kernel: arrival
on a common fixed point forces the flowed images to agree with that fixed point.

This is the formal skeleton of "different microscopic configurations in one
universality class share the same critical behaviour". -/
theorem rg_universality_basin
    (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C) (h : IsRGFixedPoint Rg cstar)
    {c : C} {n : ℕ} (harr : rgFlow Rg n c = cstar) (k : ℕ) :
    rgFlow Rg (n + k) c = cstar := by
  -- Rg^[n+k] c = Rg^[k] (Rg^[n] c) = Rg^[k] c⋆ = c⋆.
  have : rgFlow Rg (n + k) c = rgFlow Rg k (rgFlow Rg n c) := by
    unfold rgFlow
    rw [Nat.add_comm n k, Function.iterate_add_apply Rg k n]
  rw [this, harr]
  exact rgFlow_fixed Rg cstar h k

/-- **Universality, two-configuration form.**

If `c₁` and `c₂` both flow (in finitely many steps) onto the SAME fixed point
`c⋆`, then beyond their arrival scales the flow sends both to `c⋆` — they are in
one universality class.  Direct corollary of `rg_universality_basin`. -/
theorem rg_same_universality_class
    (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C) (h : IsRGFixedPoint Rg cstar)
    {c₁ c₂ : C} {n₁ n₂ : ℕ}
    (h₁ : rgFlow Rg n₁ c₁ = cstar) (h₂ : rgFlow Rg n₂ c₂ = cstar) (k : ℕ) :
    rgFlow Rg (n₁ + k) c₁ = rgFlow Rg (n₂ + k) c₂ := by
  rw [rg_universality_basin Rg cstar h h₁ k,
      rg_universality_basin Rg cstar h h₂ k]

/-! ### The full Cj.18 statement (recorded; OPEN) -/

/-- A configuration `c` is in the basin of `c⋆` (under exact finite-step
attraction). -/
def InBasin (Rg : C → C) (cstar c : C) : Prop := ∃ n : ℕ, rgFlow Rg n c = cstar

/-- **Faithful statement of Cj.18: ∃ an RG flow with a universal fixed point.**

There exists a scale-coarse-graining map `Rg : C → C` on the space of emergence
configurations together with a fixed point `c⋆` whose basin of attraction is
"universal" — modelled as: a designated nonempty class `𝒰` of configurations all
lie in the basin of the single fixed point `c⋆` (microscopically different
configurations, one fixed point = one universality class).

This `def` only RECORDS the proposition (it compiles, no `sorry`); the file does
NOT assert it is provable from A.1-A.4 — it is OPEN (see BLOCKED AT). -/
def Cj18_Statement (𝒰 : Set C) : Prop :=
  𝒰.Nonempty ∧
  ∃ (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C),
    IsRGFixedPoint Rg cstar ∧ (∀ c ∈ 𝒰, InBasin Rg cstar c)

/-- **Conditional realisation (PROVED): IF an RG map and universal fixed point
are supplied, the universality picture follows.**

Given an `Rg` with a fixed point `c⋆` whose basin contains a class `𝒰`, any two
members of `𝒰` end up flowing to the SAME configuration `c⋆` — confirming the
`Cj18_Statement` data really does encode "one universality class".  This shows
the statement is faithful and its consequences correct; it does NOT construct
`Rg` from the axioms. -/
theorem Cj18_universality_consequence
    (Rg : C → C) (cstar : C) (h : IsRGFixedPoint Rg cstar)
    {c₁ c₂ : C} (h₁ : InBasin Rg cstar c₁) (h₂ : InBasin Rg cstar c₂) :
    ∃ N : ℕ, ∀ k : ℕ, rgFlow Rg (N + k) c₁ = rgFlow Rg (N + k) c₂ := by
  obtain ⟨n₁, hn₁⟩ := h₁
  obtain ⟨n₂, hn₂⟩ := h₂
  -- flow both to c⋆ from a common scale `N := max n₁ n₂`, then match.
  refine ⟨max n₁ n₂, fun k => ?_⟩
  have e₁ : rgFlow Rg (max n₁ n₂ + k) c₁ = cstar := by
    obtain ⟨d, hd⟩ := Nat.exists_eq_add_of_le (le_max_left n₁ n₂)
    have hk : max n₁ n₂ + k = n₁ + (d + k) := by omega
    rw [hk]; exact rg_universality_basin Rg cstar h hn₁ (d + k)
  have e₂ : rgFlow Rg (max n₁ n₂ + k) c₂ = cstar := by
    obtain ⟨d, hd⟩ := Nat.exists_eq_add_of_le (le_max_right n₁ n₂)
    have hk : max n₁ n₂ + k = n₂ + (d + k) := by omega
    rw [hk]; exact rg_universality_basin Rg cstar h hn₂ (d + k)
  rw [e₁, e₂]

/-! ### Sanity / faithfulness checks -/

/-- Sanity: the identity RG map has every point as a (trivial) fixed point, and
every singleton class is its own universality class.  Confirms `Cj18_Statement`
is satisfiable for the degenerate `Rg = id` — but this is exactly the
NON-universal degenerate case (every config is its own class), illustrating why
the substantive content is the EXISTENCE of a NON-trivial coarse-graining. -/
example (c : C) : Cj18_Statement ({c} : Set C) :=
  ⟨⟨c, rfl⟩, id, c, by simp [IsRGFixedPoint, Function.IsFixedPt],
    fun x hx => ⟨0, by simp [rgFlow]; exact hx⟩⟩

